<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-09-23T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-09-23T16:00:00-05:00" n="788" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d788">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">815.00/2224: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Spencer</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-09-23T17:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">September 23,
                                        1920—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>50. Department has received despatch from American Consul at Tegucigalpa
                            dated September l,<note n="13" xml:id="d788fn13">Not printed.</note>
                            reporting that revolutionists have <pb facs="0960" n="870" xml:id="pg_870"/> entered Honduranian territory from both the
                            Nicaraguan and Salvadorean borders and have apparently made arrangements
                            for uprisings to take place in Choluteca and other cities. Please cable
                            brief report stating whether such uprisings have occurred and if so,
                            whether there is any probability that the movement will become general
                            in character.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>